definition: "Leptin is a peptide hormone produced primarily by adipocytes (fat cells) in direct proportion to fat mass — the more adipose tissue, the more leptin is secreted. Leptin acts primarily on the hypothalamus to signal energy sufficiency: high leptin tells the brain that fat stores are adequate, suppressing appetite and increasing energy expenditure. In lean, metabolically healthy individuals this system works as designed. In chronic obesity and metabolic dysfunction, the hypothalamus and other leptin-responsive tissues become resistant to leptin's signal — analogous to insulin resistance — resulting in persistently elevated leptin that no longer suppresses appetite or promotes energy expenditure, a state called leptin resistance."
why_it_matters: "Serum leptin is a direct readout of fat mass — particularly visceral fat mass — making it more metabolically specific than BMI or total body weight. Elevated leptin in the context of metabolic dysfunction reflects both the quantity of metabolically active fat tissue and the degree of leptin resistance driving the chronic hunger and energy dysregulation of obesity. Beyond appetite, leptin has significant immune and inflammatory effects: elevated leptin promotes pro-inflammatory cytokine production, activates innate immune cells, and suppresses regulatory T-cell function — mechanisms that link obesity-associated leptin elevation to systemic inflammation, autoimmune disease, and cancer risk. Leptin pairs naturally with adiponectin: the leptin:adiponectin ratio (LAR) integrates both markers into a single cardiometabolic risk index that outperforms either marker alone."

